00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:35.280
And as a music historian,
my responsibility is

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:37.320
to ask the big questions on music.

00:02:37.320 --> 00:02:38.780
So I'd like to start tonight

00:02:38.780 --> 00:02:41.400
by asking what I think
might be the biggest of all.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:44.950
And it's a simple one.

00:02:44.950 --> 00:02:48.460
Can music change your life?

00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:51.480
Can songs change your life?

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:54.640
Or let me raise it to a
slightly higher level.

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:57.530
Could music change the
life of the community?

00:02:57.530 --> 00:03:01.510
Or let me raise it to
a still higher level,

00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:04.330
could music change the
life of a whole society?

00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:08.620
And if I put this question in
the biggest, broadest terms,

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:12.370
it's can music change
the course of history?

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:14.140
Now I think that's an
important question,

00:03:14.140 --> 00:03:16.010
but it's not a question
we're familiar with.

00:03:16.010 --> 00:03:21.170
We rarely hear people ask this kind
of question, even music scholars.

00:03:21.170 --> 00:03:24.080
And I think there's
a reason for that.

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:29.450
In our society we tend to view
music as mere entertainment.

00:03:29.450 --> 00:03:34.780
It's a diversion, it's a past time.

00:03:34.780 --> 00:03:39.480
It's something we do when
we want to escape from life.

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:43.370
We don't look at music
to change our life.

00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:45.820
We more often look at music
to get away from life.

00:03:45.820 --> 00:03:48.390
It's something we do
after the responsibilities

00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:50.690
of the days are done.

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:54.200
But if you push that
view to an extreme,

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:55.590
you get to some strange endpoints.

00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:58.720
For example, there's a professor
at Harvard Steven Pinker,

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:04.730
a very eminent professor and what
he says is that the sole purpose

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:12.080
of music is to stimulate the
brain, brain stimulation.

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:16.500
In fact, he calls music
auditory cheese cake.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:18.040
That's his term, auditory
cheese cake.

00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:24.350
And he says that listening to
music is essentially no different

00:04:24.350 --> 00:04:29.640
than drinking a martini or
playing a video game or to cite one

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:33.040
of his specific examples
choosing recreational drugs,

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:36.210
recreational drugs.

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:39.400
And I think a lot of us are uneasy
about that kind of comparison.

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:42.190
I think those of us who
really care about music,

00:04:42.190 --> 00:04:45.600
those of us who have devoted our
lifetime to music we're uneasy

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:49.070
with the idea that there's
no essential difference

00:04:49.070 --> 00:04:54.500
between a Beethoven Symphony and
say a line of cocaine or LSV,

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:58.040
and we just-- something about
that doesn't feel right.

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:00.220
And I disagree with
Steven Pinker on this

00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:03.040
but I do believe he has
captured the zeitgeist.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:07.240
I believe he has captured the
way music is perceived nowadays

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:09.370
in most cultures.

00:05:09.370 --> 00:05:11.640
Music is not something of
transcendent importance,

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:14.510
it's just entertainment,
it's just diversion.

00:05:16.580 --> 00:05:21.130
But as soon as you walk away
from contemporary culture,

00:05:21.130 --> 00:05:25.640
and you take a bigger view, if
you take a larger view of music,

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:28.050 position:56%
you'll see something very different.

00:05:28.050 --> 00:05:31.550
You find a very different
attitude towards music.

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:35.030
I would like to quote an individual
named James Chalmers [assumed

00:05:35.030 --> 00:05:38.670
spelling], he was a missionary that
many years ago lived in New Guinea.

00:05:38.670 --> 00:05:39.980
And while he was there,

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:44.120
he was trying to document
the local culture.

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:47.470
And he was talking to one
of the musical performers,

00:05:47.470 --> 00:05:50.140
a drummer of the Motu tribe,
asking about the music.

00:05:50.140 --> 00:05:51.670
And the drummer said
something to him I like.

00:05:51.670 --> 00:05:57.020
He said, "The drums are
never beaten uselessly.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:06:02.050
The drums are always
played with a purpose.

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:06.260
No dance is ever danced uselessly.

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:10.870
Every dance has its purpose".

00:06:10.870 --> 00:06:12.400
Now this is a very different view

00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:14.900
from the auditory cheese
cake view, no?

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:17.710 position:56%
And if you look at other traditional
cultures, traditional societies,

00:06:17.710 --> 00:06:20.500
you see the same thing, no matter
where you are, whether you walk

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:22.570
to South America, Asia, Africa.

00:06:22.570 --> 00:06:24.870
You take for example
Native American culture.

00:06:24.870 --> 00:06:31.510
I often turn to the works of
three female ethnomusicologist,

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:35.190
who wrote extensively about Native
American music, Natalie Curtis,

00:06:35.190 --> 00:06:38.320
Alice Fletcher and a woman who
is a particular hero of mine,

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:43.640
Frances Densmore who
devoted decades of her life

00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:46.380
to documenting Native
American music.

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:49.050
And at home, I've got a
whole shelf of her books.

00:06:49.050 --> 00:06:52.240
And it's sad to say every one
of these books is out of print.

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:55.090
Every one of these books
is out of print, just sad.

00:06:55.090 --> 00:06:57.500
But she went over period
of years from community

00:06:57.500 --> 00:07:00.990
to community documenting songs
that she saw were disappearing.

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:05.350
And she wanted to document
them before they disappear.

00:07:05.350 --> 00:07:06.650
And over the course of her life,

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:09.230
she probably documented
thousands of songs.

00:07:09.230 --> 00:07:12.920
And every one of them
had its purpose.

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:15.940
Some of these songs
helped the crops grow.

00:07:15.940 --> 00:07:20.160
Some of the songs prepared
warriors to go into battle.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:24.010
Some of the songs were
involved in healing.

00:07:24.010 --> 00:07:26.220
Some of the songs preserved
tribal war,

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:28.430
or used to educate
the next generation.

00:07:28.430 --> 00:07:30.730
Some of the songs were involved
in courtship and marriage.

00:07:30.730 --> 00:07:33.310
But every song had its purpose.

00:07:33.310 --> 00:07:35.740
Every song had its meaning.

00:07:37.310 --> 00:07:40.710 position:56%
And if you look at other traditional
cultures in music in most times

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:43.500
and places, you see the same thing.

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:47.960
You see exactly the same thing.

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:51.440 position:56%
And I know that most of us nowadays,
we feel that we're too sophisticated

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:57.450 position:56%
for this, we're too sophisticated
to believe that music heals the sick

00:07:57.450 --> 00:08:01.250
or that music helps the crops grow.

00:08:01.250 --> 00:08:04.060
But speaking on the basis
of a person who has looked

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:07.610
at these issues for almost
25 years, I can tell you,

00:08:07.610 --> 00:08:10.540
you might be surprised at
the scientific evidence.

00:08:10.540 --> 00:08:11.840
You might be surprised.

00:08:11.840 --> 00:08:14.100
You know, a couple of years
ago, my son was is in 8th grade

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:16.700
and he had to do a science project.

00:08:16.700 --> 00:08:19.600
And I don't know about what
it's like here but where I am,

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:22.510 position:56%
