And I just-- People there-- I
would say, why do you do this?

00:53:29.880 --> 00:53:31.630
This is-- Because we've
always done it that way.

00:53:31.630 --> 00:53:32.930
Well that's not a reason.

00:53:32.930 --> 00:53:34.530
You can't say and, you know.

00:53:34.530 --> 00:53:36.930
But what I found, I was
amazed how many people

00:53:36.930 --> 00:53:39.050
in Oxford were listening
to country music.

00:53:39.050 --> 00:53:46.730
How many people, particularly the
people that worked in the college

00:53:46.730 --> 00:53:49.220
that weren't students, but the
people that sort of like served

00:53:49.220 --> 00:53:50.640
at the dining hall or whatever?

00:53:50.640 --> 00:53:54.520
And there was this message that
country music spoke to them

00:53:54.520 --> 00:53:57.140
in a way that I had not expected.

00:53:57.140 --> 00:53:59.380
It was very surprising
and you find--

00:53:59.380 --> 00:54:05.480
if you take some sappy company
song like "Achy Breaky Heart".

00:54:05.480 --> 00:54:09.020
That was like the number
hit in Finland, Denmark.

00:54:09.020 --> 00:54:12.280
I mean, it's amazing
how this music travels

00:54:12.280 --> 00:54:14.370
to places you don't think it would.

00:54:14.370 --> 00:54:16.760
And I believe there's
a reason for this.

00:54:16.760 --> 00:54:18.510
How do I try-- let
me articulate this.

00:54:18.510 --> 00:54:21.310
And I think it explains a lot of
what's happening in music nowadays.

00:54:21.310 --> 00:54:25.880
I believe that music today
and the love song today more

00:54:25.880 --> 00:54:32.420
than at any point in history is
embedded in people's fantasy life.

00:54:34.060 --> 00:54:36.890
And it expresses not so
much the life they have

00:54:36.890 --> 00:54:40.820
but the life they wish they had.

00:54:42.290 --> 00:54:43.600 position:56%
And let me give you another example,

00:54:43.600 --> 00:54:45.230
